author: @nessim.liamani
text: ChatGPT Summary :   In the last video, the creator highlighted a significant issue in the data science industry regarding the mismatch between recommended skills and actual job postings. They built an app analyzing data analyst job posts in the US and discovered outdated recommendations lacking evidence. The Stack Overflow developer survey inspired them to create a similar survey for data professionals. However, they faced challenges such as limited data for data professionals and technical issues with their app.  To address these issues, they embarked on building a new solution. They utilized Python to connect to an API, collecting job data globally. They engaged a data engineer to refine the data pipeline using tools like Airflow for scheduling and BigQuery for data warehousing. They also employed Spark clusters for processing large datasets efficiently.  After cleaning the data, they delved into exploring salary and skills. They found discrepancies in salary ranges in job postings and used median values for accuracy. They also identified the most in-demand skills for different roles, emphasizing SQL and Python for data professionals.  To provide accessible insights, they developed a web app using Streamlit, allowing users to filter job postings by title and explore skills and salaries. Users can now make informed decisions about skill acquisition based on real-time data.  Overall, their journey involved overcoming challenges in data collection, processing, and analysis to create a valuable resource for data professionals. They continue to seek feedback for further improvements to the website.  | Key Points | |------------------------------------------------------------------------------| | - Identified a gap between recommended skills and actual job postings in data science. | | - Built an app analyzing US data analyst job posts but faced technical issues and limited data. | | - Developed a new solution, collecting global job data using Python, Airflow, and Spark clusters. | | - Explored salary and skill data, highlighting discrepancies in salary ranges and in-demand skills. | | - Created a web app using Streamlit for users to access real-time insights on skills and salaries. | | - Open to feedback for improving the website and continuing data collection for future analysis. |

author: @mindful_minipods
text: Automated Web Scraping: Use AI-powered web scraping tools to automatically extract job data from various websites, job boards, and platforms. These tools can handle anti-scraping measures and efficiently gather data on a large scale.  Natural Language Processing (NLP) for Data Extraction: Apply NLP techniques to process the scraped data and extract relevant information such as job titles, skills, locations, and qualifications. NLP algorithms can help parse and structure the unstructured data collected from job postings.  Entity Recognition and Data Standardization: Utilize AI algorithms, such as Named Entity Recognition (NER), to identify and extract specific entities like job titles, company names, and required skills from the scraped data. This helps standardize and organize the collected information.  Data Cleaning and Deduplication: Apply AI techniques for data cleaning and deduplication to ensure the collected data is accurate and free from inconsistencies. AI algorithms can identify and remove duplicate job postings, correct errors, and normalize the data for further analysis.  Intelligent Data Filtering and Categorization: Utilize AI models, such as text classification algorithms, to filter and categorize the collected job data based on specific criteria, such as job titles, industry sectors, or skill requirements. This enables efficient organization and retrieval of relevant data for analysis.  Data Integration and Enrichment: Incorporate AI algorithms to enrich the collected job data by integrating additional relevant information from external sources. For example, AI models can gather salary data, company profiles, or industry insights to provide a more comprehensive dataset for analysis.

author: @chudchadanstud
text: You could significantly speed up you code by not printing in the for loop. Look into the actor model. You can start an actor for printing progress and another actor for fetching your data. An actor is simply a thread. You can send data between actors/threads via messages.   You could also look into IPC (Interprocess Communication), Multithreading and Multiprocessing if the actor model is too much.  The reason I recommended the actor model is that you don't need locks or mutexes

author: @spuriustadius5034
text: I respect the idea of quantifying "top skills" but there's a problem with that.   Targeting a "top skill" means that you will throw yourself into competition with a HUGE number of people. The way you make the big bucks and land elite positions, in such a situation, is by being among the top in that ocean of talent. For all but a few the path of "top skills" means competing (often globally) with people who are willing to paid far less than you are.  There's a case to made to instead target "niche" skills. It's much more feasible to become a top-choice in a lesser known technology. Ironically, it gives you more power in the job market because there's less competition. Is targeting niche skills for everyone? By definition, no, but that's the case for almost everything. Bottom line is there is no "one-size-fits-all" approach to this problem.

author: @Andy-il7kf
text: I just asked chatGPT - it answered similar to you (see below). The major difference being with yours, I know exactly what happened and therefore trust the answer. Without your transparent work, a chatGPT answer isn't any more use than all those websites you looked at that which were different from the job application data, and its worded in just as convincing language.   Honest though: I'm a data analyst and I am scared of the medium term future! Hopefully its just neo-phobia though and it will pass as I find a place in it all. I think its just the proximity of probably upcoming great change that is scary, combined with watching too many YouTube videos of the current guesses about what A.I. will do, which are often delivered in a polarised good/bad way which is unsettling. Once we start to see it play out more, all the real actual opportunities (many of which we can't guess yet) will start springing out more obviously. I hope.     Q to chatGPT: "What are the top 5 tools that data analysts need to be proficient in, in the USA?"  A from chatGPT: "The top tools that data analysts need to be proficient in can vary depending on the industry, company, and geographic location. However, here are the top five tools that are commonly used and in demand for data analysts in the USA:  SQL: Structured Query Language (SQL) is a must-have tool for data analysts in the USA, as most companies store their data in relational databases. Knowledge of SQL is critical for extracting, transforming, and querying data for analysis.  Excel: Microsoft Excel is a powerful tool for data manipulation and analysis, and it is widely used by data analysts in the USA. Excel proficiency is essential for creating pivot tables, performing statistical analysis, and visualizing data.  Python: Python is a popular programming language for data analysis, machine learning, and data visualization. Python proficiency is in high demand for data analysts in the USA, especially for working with large datasets, building models, and automating data workflows.  Tableau: Tableau is a popular data visualization tool used to create interactive dashboards and reports. Data analysts in the USA who are proficient in Tableau can create compelling visualizations that communicate data insights to stakeholders effectively.  R: R is a programming language commonly used for statistical analysis and data visualization. Although not as widely used as Python in the USA, proficiency in R is still a valuable skill for data analysts working in fields like finance and healthcare."

author: @rugbyf0rlife
text: I always wondered what "data jobs" actually did. It always seemed so buzzwordy and overhyped to me. This video showed me what actual work goes into data, and I appreciate the salaries more now. Although I still think the volume for the wage is overblown, for example, Luke just created this database almost by himself which answers the question for an entire industry. It seems it took him a few weeks of solid work to get this done. So realistically, how many data workers do you actually need worldwide? I feel like most of them are just doing work that other people have done elsewhere, but hasn't been monetized/shared via an app.  i.e 10 data analysts make 10 internal applications for 10 companies and are all paid $120k/year. Rather than making a singular app and then licensing that app out to all 10 companies, those 10 companies have each spent probably $40,000 worrth of time and investment to make the same thing, i.e 400k to solve a 40k problem.  This is why modern data companies are so valuable, and would be more efficient than different companies in different industries having their own data employees for their own internal use.

text: Perhaps an automated way of identifying what skills are mentioned in job postings would be to see what terms are mentioned more often in your dataset of postings than in "typical" (i.e., unrelated to data work) English phrases.
